{"key":"processedPost-12297926","value":{"id":12297926,"first":12296074,"last":12303386,"when":1269961323,"utime":"03/30/10 06:02 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Mycjunky said:</strong><br />I would say no simply because it's really not even necessary to pasteurize coir in the first place so if your temps aren't perfect it doesn't matter anyways for that tek.</blockquote><br />Incorrect.&nbsp; Coir needs at least some heat treatment in order for the mycelium to have access to the food within.&nbsp; Coir is more forgiving in that mold spores rarely germinate on it, but coir still needs to be pasteurized.&nbsp; Many growers have attempted to hydrate and use coir with very poor results as far as fruiting performance.<br />Manure should be maintained at the center of the substrate at 140F to 160F for at least one hour, but 90 minutes is better.&nbsp; Any method you use that achieves the above will work.<br />RR"}}